<Rating>1< /Rating>< review>
Great place to live if your idea of home is paying 3k to have a blaring fire alarm keeping you up for an hour at 3am in the morning for no good reason. This happens often and yet management still has not figured out a way to improve the system or communication around false alarms. As a result, the building currently has no good way to signal to residents in the event that their lives are actually in danger. This situation is perfectly representative of the lack of care and regard for residents here. On the bright side, the building is getting a revamp of the HVAC system to use Nest thermostats, when the current ones are still perfectly functional. I will let the reader conclude why they might be investing time and money into doing this instead of fixing critical safety systems.

Regardless, they will justify to themselves a 16% year over year rent raise after giving you a discounted first year. Don‚Äôt be fooled by it. The management is negligent when it comes to your actual safety and security. It is not worth investing a move to this building.</review>

<Time>1551402667583<//Time><Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
I have enjoyed my time living at this particular apartment complex. I have lived here for a little over a year. The kitchen in my apartment is state of the art and I have enjoyed this since I love cooking. The view is also spectacular from my windows. What has made my stay here great is the amazing staff that they have. Jay has been instrumental with providing great hospitality. He has been very patient and helpful when I contact him. Also, the location of this apartment complex is great. There are so many things nearby within walking distance such as restaurants and entertainment. I have been trying to have a healthier lifestyle so it has been amazing to have Whole Foods located so close to me to buy my groceries. There is also a gym located in the apartment complex with really good machinery and I have heard that it is the best gym in downtown Los Angeles. I have enjoyed doing yoga in particular but they also have boxing and spinning available. It has also been great to have access to two pools that are always kept clean. For those of you that like going to the movie theater, there is one available as well and I have enjoyed going to it. Also, I do not take advantage of it everyday since I am not a coffee lover but they do provide free coffee 24/7 which is just wow. There is also a Wells Fargo located in the building for those of you that are bank members there. I also want to give a shout out to all the cleaners that keep the property clean and looking fresh. Maria for instance, always makes sure the coffee machine is spotless in the mornings. Overall, I feel that you do get what you pay for and totally recommend this place to everyone whether you are living alone, with a partner/spouse, or with a family including pets.<//Text>

<GmapID>0x80c2c7b50f352dfd:0x359ba7d9bf687b50< /GmapID><Review>Luxury Apartment Great living, Great Entertainment in the area  Delete

I would like to give you my experience of Eighth and Grand and the manager Stephanie W. I moved to Eighth and Grand in July. I actually came and toured the property once in May and again in June. The lobby was playing really good music. I was asked if I wanted a cup of coffee or water. I went to the coffee bar and made a Caf√© Mocha. I wanted to stay there a while and enjoy my surroundings. It was very welcoming and inviting.

I toured with the manager Stephanie since all the other leasing agents were busy with other people and I didn‚Äôt have an appointment. Stephanie said she would take me on the tour but said she was fairly new to Eighth and Grand. She didn‚Äôt seem like she was new at all to Eighth and Grand. <Text>I have to update my review because over the course of the last year (starting about March 2018 to current), my experience living at 8th and Grand has declined significantly. I will try my best to give an overall fair assessment of what it‚Äôs like living here.

Cons:
From the horrendous paint project that took over 6 months to complete and caused serious inconveniences to residents (ie -having your unit being blocked from sunlight for weeks, and restricted use of amenities) to issues with packages being routinely dismissed by parcel pending and the front desk staff due to lack of space (and management taking a low key attitude and failing to come up with a solution for weeks), to trash chutes being broken, and now, to fire alarms that keep reoccurring with majority of staff who are not properly trained on how to shut down the system. I've been understanding time and time again, but as I sit here at 3:30 A.M. with the fire alarm ringing in my ears as the staff tries to "handle" the situation for over 20 minutes, I am infuriated.

To be fair, I will list some of the pros as well.

Pros:

- excellent maintenance staff. Can‚Äôt get any better. Shout out to Milton, Willie, and Jay.
-front desk staff (Gary and Kenny go above and beyond expectations to help out all residents).
- Brittany is the assistant manager who is very responsive to emails and always makes sure resident complaints are heard in a timely manner.
-amenities are great, including an above average apartment gym (could use someone to restock towels more often).

< review>
I was super excited when I moved into this building. Living above a Whole Foods, the amenities, modern apartments, etc. Now 10 months later, I can't wait for my lease to end.

Pros:
- New Building
- Whole Foods
- 24hr doorman
- Responsive maintenance team
- Rooftop pool
- Front desk staff

Cons:
- Why is the A/C unit so loud? You can't even watch TV without it being so disruptive.
- The fire alarms. Yes I know that the building is still being built, but come on. Every week or so they go off, especially in the middle of the night. It's fine if you have to run tests during the day, but waking me up in the middle of the night for "false" alarms, is not ok.
- Why is there no service elevator? Whenever someone moves in, there is only one elevator functioning in the lobby.
- Airbnb is illegal in the building, yet management turns a blind eye to it. There are lots of random people walking around with access to the building, which does not make it feel safe.
- Recent water damage: The fire alarm went off again on 9/1 and this time there was water damage. Instead of notifying the residents that there would be major construction, the management decided to just start the work and annoy the residents. Now they want to do work in our apartments, but expect us to live in them while the work is being completed, for a week. This construction involves new dry wall, fans and lots of plastic sheets everywhere.
- Bad management: They don't respond to emails and they don't care about your concerns. As long as the rent is paid, they don't care...

This building calls itself a luxury building and it is when you look at how much the apartments cost, but not when you think about the fact that you really can't enjoy it.

Look elsewhere if you're looking for a new apartment. The amenities may draw you in, but you'll regret it once you actually move in.<//review>

I am a student who goes to USC, who is extremely disappointed with the service I have received at 8th and Grand apartments. When I first took a tour of the complex, I was very impressed with the place and its wonderful amenities. I was excited when I finally moved in on the 28th of July. Rather than offering to help, she made it seem as if it was not her problem. I then went to the general manager, who had the nerve to immediately suggest that I must have brought the cockroaches with me when I moved in since they had never had a roach problem before. I informed her that this was impossible because I had not even moved in any of my stuff with me yet. The cockroach issue got worse: I kept finding them on my patio, in my bathroom and in my kitchen. When I slept on the floor the first night, I woke up the next day with red marks all over my body, the kind of thing you get from dust mites. Cockroaches and dust mites are the worse for someone struggling with asthma like me. I complained again and a pest control guy was brought in to inspect. But the man hovered in my apartment for 5 minutes, said there was no infestation and went away without doing a thing. I have now been here for a whole week and, despite repeatedly speaking to the building manager, general manager and everyone worth a damn that works here, nothing has been done to rectify this situation. The only suggestion made so far is that I should transfer to a different apartment; of course, this means I have to pay $500-1000 just to do that, simply because they aren‚Äôt willing to help me out! I am busy currently studying for my MCAT and do not have the ability to simply make money materialize out of nowhere and move apartments. I have had to stay with a friend over the past few days just because the situation here has become extremely unpleasant. I have been in America for four years and had never seen a cockroach until I moved into this apartment, let alone expect something as bad as this. <userid>118283082462055892132< /userid><name>Whitney DuBose<//name><Time>1468530914764<//Time>< rate>
1<//rate>
< Review>
POSITIVES:
-Layouts are a great use of space. Entire building is nicely styled and decorated. Convenient location to restaurants, gyms, Whole Foods, etc...Fitness classes provided at no charge. Security/Maintenence staff and Patrick at front desk are welcoming and accommodating. Color scheme is neutral and chic. Large bathrooms and tubs/showers.

CONCERNS:
-Ceiling fan cannot be turned past 2 without loud squeaking. Checked out by maintenance and cannot be fixed.
-Air compressors in above floor continuously make noise when AC turns on/off or intermittently. Again told nothing can be done and that this was a design flaw. Happens at least three times an hour if not more.
-Thin doors and walls mean you can hear everything outside.
-Insanely small closet.
-Haphazard paint job inside and on balcony (paint on doors and floors).
-No explanations of after-hours false fire alarms or indication that it is in fact false. This does not include the scheduled tests.
-Event details and times are usually incorrect or changed at last minute
-No notification of work such as repainting the apartment doors. One day I came home to find that my door was just about to be painted and I was told I could enter my apartment but could not leave for several hours until the paint was dry. I was never notified this was to be done.
-Amenities are frequently rented for 10 or more hours at a time, or days at a time (without notice or last minute notice to residents).
-No timeline given for amenity openings or notifications of delays for months at a time.
-Gym opening was delayed for months with no notice but announced on social media as if it had opened. I went to the gym and it was closed and was only told it would open "soon." The same happened with the lounge and pool area.
-Long wait times for elevators because there are only two that go to the 1st floor for 700 residents
-Management does not respond in a timely manner to requests or complaints and it can be weeks or months without a reply.
--Management seems largely inexperienced, overwhelmed, and aloof. When presented with concerns, they "try" but do not actually solve anything or make concessions.
-AirBnB has a large presence in this building and disregard community rules.
-I do not feel safe living in a building where anyone can rent a room for a night and have access to the entire building.

All in all, the community spaces feel like "luxury" (when not reserved) but the day to day living in this building is anything but. The positives of living here are things you can find almost anywhere in downtown right now and do not make this place worth the cost or trouble of living here.<//Review>

Payed over $12 for a horribly made  sandwich ü•™üòí<//review>
< Name>
Enrique Thomas</Name>
</record></dataset><record>
< Review>
This place is pretty good. Kind of random items. Don't expect to find soda! Lol. They seem to focus on healthy food, which is nice.

There are a couple chairs and tables, and a little sandwhich counter, and salad counter in the back. You can also buy packaged food.

We went in looking for lunch. I got these AMAZING pre packaged little things. I can't remember what they are called. I had them years ago at an Arabic wedding. They are grape leaves stuffed with rice, onion, lemon, and a few other things. They are amazing!!!

I got a pastrami sandwhich, which was delish! They are panini style. I got mine with extra pickle, and it was delish! Very filling, and generous on the meat.

Hubby got a turkey pesto sandwhich. He liked it. He's not huge on pesto. But gave it a try. I thought it was really good.

They don't have mayo. At least not mayo like you know. They guy helping us did say they have a mayo substitute in the back, and he went and got it for us. It was ok. Kind of no flavor, really.

We also got a peanut butter cookie that was really good. A cute little spot. Interesting. Only thing that bugged me, the guy helping went from handling cash at the register, to touching our food, no gloves, and didn't wash.<//Review>

<UserId.>111436658337991156355< /UserId.><Name>Brittaney<//Name>< Time>
1512629935310< /Time>
< Rating>
1< /Rating>
< text>
------BEWARE------'

Things I didnt know but will be useful

Do NOT get Hertz insurance they dont care about their cars, as long as you have your insurance your fine. You also cant cancel their insurance over the phone. Just make sure they document all the scratches and dents before you leave because there will be plenty.

Also, dont allow them to fill the car back up with gas because you can find a cheap off brand of gas just to get the car on the line it started at.

Definitely make sure the tags and registration is up to date in the vehicle because again they dont care if you get a ticket you are responsible. They will also assess a $30 Administrative fee.

If you can avoid giving them your bank cards they have an option to do a cash deposit. A bill to estalish residency, a check stub and id will be sufficient. (They hate doing the cash deposit because it takes more work and they can charge you for extra on your bank card).

If you can avoid the Hertz in Gardena, they close early through the week and close even earlier on Saturday. Go to LAX its open 24 hours. Not to mention, Gardena have 3 employees so be prepared to wait.

If you need to change the car say because they forgot to update all of the registration, be prepared that you can not exchange the car at another location so if you work or like to sleep in on Saturdays you have to get up bright and early to fix their mistake.

Its useless to complain because everyone is in a meeting hence why there is three people working there.

If you have a reservation or just returning a car be prepared to wait in a long line.

Hope that after 500 miles the maintenance light doesnt show up causing the car to act and burn more gas. Just hope that your experience is not as bad as mine.</text>
